Launching `pwsh.exe` via WSH, such as from a VBScript, seemingly causes PowerShell not to find well-known assemblies such as `System.Windows.Forms` that you can normally load with `Add-Type -Assembly`

Note: This is a regression of sorts from Windows PowerShell, though the technological foundation has changed: Windows PowerShell looks in the GAC, whereas PowerShell Core - due to there no longer being a GAC in .NET Core - seemingly looks in `$PSHOME`.

Note that the problem can be reproduced with both WSH executables, `cscript.exe` (console) and `wscript.exe` (GUI).

# Steps to reproduce

Run the following Pester test on Windows:

```powershell
Describe "WSH-launched CLI command should find well-known assemblies" {

  BeforeAll {
    Push-Location testdrive:\
    $outFile = (Convert-Path .) + 'out.txt'
    'powershell', 'pwsh' | ForEach-Object {
      "CreateObject(`"WScript.Shell`").Run(`"$_.exe -noprofile -c Add-Type -AssemblyName System.Windows.Forms; `$Error[0] > $outFile`")" > "test_$_.vbs"
    }
  }

  It "Can locate System.Windows.Forms" {

    'powershell', 'pwsh' | ForEach-Object {

      Remove-Item -ErrorAction Ignore $outFile

      & ./"test_$_.vbs"

      While (-not (Get-Item -EA Ignore $outFile)) {
        Write-Host . -NoNewline
        Start-Sleep -Milliseconds 300
      }
      Write-Host
      Get-Content $outFile | Should -BeNullOrEmpty
    }

  }

  AfterAll {
    Start-Sleep 1 # Sleep a little 
    Pop-Location
  }

}
```

# Expected behavior

The tests should pass.

# Actual behavior

The test with `pwsh.exe` fails.

```none
 Expected $null or empty, but got @('Add-Type : Cannot find path 'C:\Users\jdoe\AppData\Local\Temp\07a8351f-062f-4253-bf76-8994223a491b\System.Windows.Forms.dll' because it does not exist.'
```

That is, the `System.Windows.Forms.dll` assembly wasn't found in PowerShell's own home folder (`$PSHOME`) even though it is present there. (try `Get-Item "$PSHOME\System.Windows.Forms.dll"`)

# Environment data

```none
PowerShell Core 7.0.0-preview.5
```
